==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*aska-, *aski-'', ultimately from Indo-European ''*ōs-'' ‘ash’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[ask]] (Dutch [[es]]), Old High German [[asca]] (German [[Esche]]), Old Norse [[askr]] (Swedish [[ask]]).  The IE root, in various forms, is also the source of Greek [[οξύα]] ‘beech, spear-shaft’, Latin [[ornus]], Russian [[ясень]] ‘ash’, Lithuanian [[uosis|úosis]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /æʃ/

===Noun===
'''æsc''' ''m'' (Plural: [[ascas]])
# the [[ash]] tree
# the [[ash]] shaft of a [[spear]]
# the runic letter ᚫ, or its romanised equivalent ''Æ, æ''.

